<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-550-948  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 550 948.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  August 21 1989 v23 n34 p29(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>From three mainframes to one with PR/SM. (IBM's PR/SM partitioningfacility on an IBM mainframe)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gibson, Stanley.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Financial Technologies Inc, a bank service bureau, has replacedits three IBM 370 architecture mainframes with one 3090 180S byusing IBM's PR/SM partitioning facility.andP;  The single mainframeruns two partitions under MVS/XA and one under VM/SP with IBM'shigh-performance option.andP;  One partition runs VM, using 25 percentof the CPU, a second runs MVS in production and uses an average of70 percent of the CPU and the last, also running MVS, uses theremaining CPU capacity and is used for testing.andP;  Partitioning hassaved the company money on hardware and software, since it is lessexpensive to license software for one CPU running in severalpartitions than it is to license software for more than one CPU.andO;Some of the cost savings are offset by the need to pay a higherlicense fee for a CPU in a more expensive graduated pricingcategory but that does not negate the overall savings.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Financial Technologies Inc. (automation)International Business Machines Corp. (products).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Product:   IBM 3090 180S (Mainframe computer) (usage).andO;Topic:     Mainframe computersBusiness PlanningService BureausCost ReductionCase Study.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>